### ggplot2
# hadley wickham's tidyverse
# https://www.tidyverse.org (r packages for data science)
# install.packages("tidyverse")
# https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org (ggplot2 is a system for declarative creating graphics,
# based on the grammar of graphics (https://www.springer.com/it/book/9780387245447) 
# which is a coherent system for describing and building graphs)
# https://r4ds.had.co.nz/data-visualisation.html
# https://www.rstudio.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/ggplot2-cheatsheet.pdf

require(ggplot2)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
data(mpg)
#str(mpg)
#?mpg
# ggplot() is used to construct the initial plot object, and is almost always followed by + 
# to add component to the plot
# ggplot() creates a coordinate system that you can add layers to

####################
### One variable ###
####################

# histogram
ggplot(data=mpg, aes(displ))+
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(data=mpg, aes(displ))+
  geom_histogram(bins =15, fill = 2)

# bar plot
ggplot(data=mpg)+
  geom_bar(aes(drv), fill = 2)

####################
### Two variables ##
####################
# scatterplot
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point()

ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

# alternatively
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point()

# geom_point() adds a layer of points to your plot, which creates a scatterplot
# each geom function in ggplot2 takes a mapping argument
# # a geom is the geometrical object that a plot uses to represent data
# compare the following two graphs
# the mapping argument is always paired with aes(), and the x and y arguments of 
# aes() specify which variables to map to the x and y axes
# aesthetic mappings describe how variables in the data are mapped to visual properties 
# (aesthetics) of geoms
# ggplot2 comes with many geom functions that each add a different type of layer to a plot
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, method = "lm") 
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth() # by deafult fits a polynomial surface
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

# Note: all the geom functions need aesthetics!
# If the aesthetics are not specified in geom_point(),
# they will be taken from ggplot(),
# if they are specified nowhere, you will get an error.

# Boxplots
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(y = hwy)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

# Using colours to represent two variables: colouring bar plots
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = class, fill = drv), show.legend=FALSE)

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = class, fill = drv))

# Using colours to represent two variables: coloring histograms
ggplot(data=mpg, aes(hwy))+
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = drv, col = drv), alpha= 0.7, bins =15)

#######################
### Three variables ###
#######################
# playing with aesthetic mappings: adding more variables
# colour, size, alpha, shape
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, 
                           colour = class))

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = class))
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

# Warning message:
# Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = cty))

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, 
                           alpha = cty))

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, 
                           shape = class))
## Warning: The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values because
## more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate; you have 7. Consider
## specifying shapes manually if you must have them.
## Warning: Removed 62 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

# only uses six shapes!
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy), colour="red")

# here, the color doesnt convey information about a variable, 
# but only changes the appearance of the plot, thus should be added
# outside the aes()
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy), shape=5)

#################################
### Global vs. Local mappings ###
#################################

# global mappings
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method='lm')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, linetype = drv, color=drv)) +
  geom_smooth() +
  geom_point()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

# local and global mappings
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point(aes(color=drv)) +
  geom_smooth(method='lm', se=FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = drv)) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(linetype = drv, color = drv))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

### facets
# One way to add additional variables is with aesthetics. 
# Another way, particularly useful for categorical variables that do noe have many levels, 
# is to split your 
# plot into facets, subplots that each display one subset of the data.
# facet_grid() forms a matrix of panels defined by row and column faceting variables. 
# It is most useful when you have two discrete variables, and all combinations of the 
# variables exist in the data. If you have only one variable with many levels, 
# try facet_wrap().
ggplot(data = mpg) +
    geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class)) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class))

# facet_grid(x ~ y) will display x*y plots even if some plots are empty
# facet_wrap(x ~ y) on the other hand, displays only the plots having actual values
ggplot(data = mpg) +
    geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
    facet_grid(drv ~ class)

ggplot(data = mpg) +
    geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
    facet_grid(. ~ class)

ggplot(data = mpg) +
    geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
    facet_grid(. ~ cyl)

# which is the same as
ggplot(data = mpg) +
    geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
    facet_wrap(~ cyl, nrow = 1)

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
    geom_point(mapping = aes(color = class)) +
    geom_smooth(data = dplyr::filter(mpg, class == "subcompact"), 
                se = FALSE, method = 'lm')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

# local data argument in geom_smooth() overrides the global data argument
# ?geom_smooth
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
    geom_smooth(data = dplyr::filter(mpg, class != "2seater"), se = FALSE, method = 'lm') +
    geom_point(mapping = aes(color = class))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, method = 'lm') +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = class))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

### statistical transformations and more geometric objects
ggplot(data = diamonds) +
    geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut))

# On the x-axis, the chart displays cut, a variable from diamonds.
# On the y-axis, it displays count, but count is not a variable in diamonds! 
# Where does count come from?
# Many graphs, like scatterplots, plot the raw values of your dataset. Other graphs, 
# like bar charts, calculate new values to plot.
# The algorithm used to calculate new values for a graph is called a stat, 
# short for statistical transformation.
# geom_bar()
?geom_bar
## starting httpd help server ...
##  done
# stat = "count"
# stats and geoms can be generally used interchangeably
ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
    stat_count(mapping = aes(x = cut))

margin.table(Titanic,1)
## Class
##  1st  2nd  3rd Crew 
##  325  285  706  885
df <- data.frame(margin.table(Titanic,1))
ggplot(data = df) +
    geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = Class, y = Freq), stat="identity")   

### coordinate systems
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy)) + 
    geom_boxplot() +
    coord_flip()

    geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = reorder(Model,mpg), y = mpg),stat="identity") +
    labs(title = "Fuel economy",x = "Model",y = "Miles per Galon") +
    coord_flip()

### graphics for communication
# from exploration to communication 
# install.packages("tidyverse")
library(tidyverse)
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = class)) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, method = 'lm') +
  labs(title = "Fuel efficiency generally decreases with engine size",
    subtitle = "Two seaters (sports cars) are an exception because of their light weight",
    x = "Engine displacement (in litres)",
    y = "Highway miles per gallon",
    caption = "Data from fueleconomy.gov",
    colour = "Car type")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

# annotations
best_in_class <- mpg %>%
    group_by(class) %>%
    filter(row_number(desc(hwy)) == 1)

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
    geom_point(aes(colour = class)) +
    geom_text(aes(label = model), data = best_in_class)

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
    geom_point(aes(colour = class)) +
    geom_label(aes(label = model), data = best_in_class, nudge_y = 2, alpha = .5)

#install.packages("ggrepel")
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
    geom_point(aes(colour = class)) +
    geom_point(size = 1, shape = 1, data = best_in_class) +
    ggrepel::geom_label_repel(aes(label = model), data = best_in_class)

# themes
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = class)) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  theme_bw()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = class)) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  theme_classic()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = class)) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  theme_dark()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

# legend
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point(aes(colour = class)) +
  theme(legend.position = "left")

#### Practice exercise: Find the bug
# Consider the following dataset where you want to create two boxplots
# given variable x, and additionally split by b. You thus expect two 
# boxplots for A (one corresponding to b=1 and one to b=2) and 
# two boxplots for B (one for b=1 and one for b=2).
# Why this code is only generating two boxplots?

df_shd.dag = data.frame(x = rep(c("A","B"), 40, replace = T),
                        z = rep(c("1","2"), 40, replace = T),
                        y = rnorm(80))

ggplot(data = df_shd.dag, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = x)) +
  stat_boxplot(geom = "errorbar") +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = TRUE)
